<h2>The Question</h2>
<p>
  The reveal-nav ruling (<a href="/backlog/609-candidate-standard-reveal-navigation-menus-mega-menu-hover-d/">#609</a>)
  drew a clean line: an own-thesis component family earns a block; a <em>pure-composition meta-component</em>
  (nav-list + disclosure + anchor + hover-intent, wired together) earns <strong>no block</strong> — but the
  author still needs ergonomic help to assemble one. The complement #609 named is a zero-lock-in
  <strong>"build-your-own-component" composition assembler</strong> in devtools
  (<a href="/backlog/646-devtools-composition-assembler-build-your-own-component-for-/">#646</a>): a workbench
  that wires WE primitives into a meta-component and <em>emits an ejectable recipe</em> — no runtime framework,
  because <strong>the emitted recipe is the standard</strong> (<em>impl-is-not-a-standard</em>;
  <em>minimize-lock-in</em>). This survey grounds the shape decision
  <a href="/backlog/652-assembler-emit-format-its-relationship-to-the-623-626-workbe/">#652</a>: <em>what format
  does a preset emit on eject</em>, and <em>where does the tool live relative to the
  <a href="/backlog/623-web-docs-feature-pipeline-inventory-workbench-tools-derive-i/">#623–627</a> Web Docs
  catalog pipeline</em>?
</p>

<h2>Recommendation (at a glance)</h2>
<ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 list-disc pl-5">
  <li><strong>Eject payload = plain markup + declarative wiring attributes</strong> — the dominant
    "you own the code, no runtime" model (shadcn/ui, Webstudio, Webflow). This is a <em>forced invariant</em>
    under #609's constraints, not a real fork. <em>Confidence: high.</em></li>
  <li><strong>The survey reshaped Fork 1:</strong> "markup vs CEM vs bespoke JSON" was a false trichotomy —
    those three sit on <em>different layers</em> (a payload, a descriptor, a distribution wrapper) and
    <strong>coexist</strong>, they are not rival payloads.</li>
  <li><strong>CEM is an additional <em>export</em>, not the recipe</strong> — already settled by
    <a href="/backlog/626-map-workbench-features-to-we-standards-which-intents-blocks-/">#626</a> as WE's
    component-API-metadata protocol; the assembler emits one describing the composed meta-component's API,
    the same as any block. It never carries the composition wiring.</li>
  <li><strong>Home = a standalone devtools surface reading the shared registries read-only</strong> — keeps
    the catalog/authoring split clean (bias-toward-separation; one-capability-many-consumers).
    <em>Confidence: med-high.</em></li>
  <li><strong>Preset storage = a WE-owned registry following the shadcn <code>registry-item</code> shape</strong>
    — proven, CLI-friendly, native-ecosystem; distinct from the <code>workbench*</code> vocabulary it also reads.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Prior art — the eject-to-ownership landscape</h2>
<table class="text-sm">
  <thead><tr><th>Source</th><th>Model</th><th>What it emits</th><th>Lesson for #652</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>shadcn/ui</strong> (the canonical model)</td>
      <td>"Not a component library — a code <em>distribution</em> platform." You copy source <em>into</em> your
        repo and own it; no runtime dependency, modify freely.</td>
      <td>Plain TS/JSX source files. A thin <code>registry-item.json</code> wrapper
        (<code>{name, type: "registry:block", files:[{path, content}], registryDependencies}</code>) is the
        <em>transport</em> the CLI installs — it carries the code, it is not a replacement for it.</td>
      <td>Decisive precedent: the ejectable artifact is <em>plain code you own</em>; a structured manifest is a
        <em>distribution wrapper around</em> that code, not a rival "bespoke schema." This splits #652 Fork 1's
        conflated options onto two layers.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Webstudio / Webflow / Builder.io</strong></td>
      <td>Visual builders that "export and host anywhere."</td>
      <td>Clean, semantic, production-ready HTML/CSS/JS — explicitly to avoid vendor lock-in.</td>
      <td>Confirms eject-to-plain-platform-code is the mainstream zero-lock-in answer for an <em>assembler</em>
        specifically (not just a library); honours native-first.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Custom Elements Manifest (CEM)</strong></td>
      <td>Declarative JSON describing a component's <em>API</em> (attributes/props/events/slots/CSS-API).</td>
      <td>A <em>descriptor</em> of a component's surface — consumed by api-viewer, Storybook-wc, IDEs.</td>
      <td>Describes a component's <em>API</em>, never its internal composition wiring. So it is an
        <em>additional export</em> of the assembled meta-component (already WE's protocol per #626), not the
        recipe body. Different layer again.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Web Components / Lit</strong></td>
      <td>"Minimize lock-in: native browser standards, no build step, update one component at a time."</td>
      <td>Framework-agnostic custom elements.</td>
      <td>Reinforces the #609 <em>no-runtime-framework</em> invariant — the recipe must round-trip into a real
        page with nothing the platform can't already render.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Storybook CSF / web-types</strong></td>
      <td>Authoring formats for examples + IDE metadata.</td>
      <td>Story / completion descriptors.</td>
      <td>Ingest sources (#624/#426), not eject targets — confirms the assembler's <em>output</em> is not these.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>The load-bearing insight — three layers, not three rival formats</h2>
<p>
  #652 Fork 1 framed "plain markup <em>vs</em> CEM-aligned descriptor <em>vs</em> bespoke recipe JSON" as a
  trichotomy. The shadcn precedent dissolves it: those three are not competing payloads — they live on
  <strong>three orthogonal layers that coexist</strong>:
</p>
<ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 list-disc pl-5">
  <li><strong>The ejectable payload</strong> (what the author owns) → <em>plain markup + WE declarative wiring</em>.
    Forced by #609's "output is the standard / no runtime / round-trips into a page" constraints. shadcn proves
    the owned artifact is always plain code.</li>
  <li><strong>The API descriptor</strong> (an optional export of the result) → <em>CEM</em>, already WE's
    metadata protocol (#626). Describes the composed meta-component's surface; never the wiring.</li>
  <li><strong>The distribution wrapper</strong> (how presets are stored/shared, the <em>input</em> side) → a
    thin <em>registry-item</em>-shaped manifest carrying the payload. This is the same artifact that answers
    Fork 2's "shared registry" — the preset store the assembler reads.</li>
</ul>
<p>
  So Fork 1 collapses to a <strong>forced invariant</strong> (plain markup+wiring payload) plus two
  <em>support-all additional emit targets</em> (CEM descriptor, already-settled; distribution wrapper, folded
  into Fork 2). The bespoke project-facing recipe schema — a WE-owned JSON the author is handed <em>instead of</em>
  markup — is the one genuinely <em>rejected</em> branch: it is exactly the lock-in <em>minimize-lock-in</em>
  refuses, and shadcn shows it is unnecessary (the wrapper carries plain code, it does not replace it).
</p>

<h2>Classification (the #652 build plan)</h2>
<p>
  Per the per-fork classification pass: the assembler is <strong>devtools</strong> (a tool consulted at
  authoring time, not a running-app seam) → zero lock-in, no protocol. The emitted recipe is the standard
  artifact (a page). The preset store is a <strong>registry</strong> the tool reads — a shared source of truth
  (one-capability-many-consumers), classified alongside the <code>workbenchFeatures.json</code> /
  <code>workbenchTools.json</code> vocabulary the catalog pipeline (#623–627) also reads. Honouring
  <em>bias-toward-separation</em>, the authoring tool and the catalog/served-product surface stay distinct
  consumers of those registries rather than one fused surface.
</p>

